<DOC><DOCNO> AP900425-0230 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-90 0231EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Milken-Chronology     04-25 0509</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Milken-Chronology,0529</SECOND><HEAD>Important Dates in the Michael Milken Case</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Milken Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here is a chronology of major developments in the prosecution offormer Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. junk bond chief Michael Milken:   Nov. 14, 1986 _ Stock speculator Ivan Boesky pays $100 millionto settle charges of insider trading on information supplied byinvestment banker Dennis Levine in 1985 and 1986. He also agrees tocooperate with investigators and to plead guilty to a singlecriminal charge. Boesky later is sentenced to three years in prison.   Late 1986 _ Published reports link Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.high-yield bond financier Michael Milken to an illegal insidertrading network led by Boesky.   Sept. 7, 1988 _ The Securities and Exchange Commission accusesDrexel, Milken and three others of violating a wide range ofsecurities laws, most of them in connection with Boesky.   Dec. 21 _ Drexel agrees to plead guilty to six felonies and paya record $650 million in fines and restitution to settle thebiggest securities fraud case in history. Drexel also must settlerelated SEC charges and cooperate with the government investigation.   March 29, 1989 _ A federal grand jury indicts Milken, hisbrother, Lowell, and former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg on 98counts of racketeering and fraud largely based on informationsupplied by Boesky. Potential penalties and fines under the countsamount to about $12 billion plus possible prison terms.   April 7 _ The Milkens plead innocent. Newberg enters an innocentplea later.   April 13 _ Drexel and the SEC announce a settlement of the civilfraud case that subjects the firm to federal monitoring for threeyears and forces it to sever ties with Milken.   June 15 _ Milken resigns after 19 years at Drexel to form hisown consulting firm. Lowell Milken quits to return to practicinglaw.   Sept. 11 _ Drexel pleads guilty to six felonies and beginspaying more than $650 million in fines, penalties and interest.   Feb. 13, 1990 _ Drexel's parent company files for federalbankruptcy court protection after failing to meet short-term debtpayments. The securities firm, once the nation's fifth-largest,starts laying off its 5,400 employees.   March 19 _ Prosecutors promise to bring a new indictment withbroader charges against Milken by the week of April 16.   April 4 _ Boesky is released from federal custody aftercompleting two years of a three-year term.   April 19 _ Four months of negotiations intensify between thegovernment and Milken for a possible plea bargain to settle thecase as a deadline looms for the new indictment.   April 20 _ Sources say Milken agrees to plead guilty to sixfelony counts and pay fines and restitution totaling $600 millionunder a plea agreement with prosecutors.   April 24 _ Milken pleads guilty to six criminal charges andagrees to pay fines and restitution totaling $600 million to settlehis case. The charges of securities and tax law violations are muchless serious than the insider trading and racketeering countsbrought against him in the government's indictment.</TEXT></DOC>